<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-217-407 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 386 019</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 25 1991 v8 n8 p69(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Who ya gonna trust for long-term support? (changes in vendorstrategy can lead to disaster for customers whose systems arediscontinued) (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dodge, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   3Com Corp. (Product discontinuation).andO;Ticker:    COMS.andO;Product:   3andplus;Open 2.0 (Network operating system) (Usage)OS/2 LAN Manager (Network management software) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Product DiscontinuationComputer industryMarketing StrategyVendor RelationsEquipment Acquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Who can you trust?andP;  That question is burning through the collective minds ofinformation-systems (IS) departments in the wake of the OS/2 and Windowsconfusion.andM;Users have long been victimized by non-support and splintered migrationpaths.andP;  Historically, IS departments took refuge in the IBM strategy.andM;Today, alternatives to IBM appear to abound, but once trust and coherence aretaken into account, the options evaporate.andP;  With technology at the foundationof many corporate re-engineering and quality programs, faith placed in vendorrelationships is extremely high.andM;The following is a frightening example of a relationship gone awry.andM;A large American insurance company with 80 LANs comprising 4,800 nodespioneered the use of 3andplus;Open.andP;  Its long-standing dependence on 3Com'svalue-added services pretty much dictated the migration to 3andplus;Open from thepreceding product, 3andplus;Share.andP;  3andplus;Open is based on the Microsoft OS/2 LANManager.andM;The migration was hairy, but it was completed without much disruption.andO;Shortly after 3andplus;Open was operational, Microsoft upgraded LAN Manager from 1.1to 2.0, with many new features.andP;  3Com included 2.0 with 3andplus;Open last year.andM;The upgrade was a training and support nightmare, but the company muddledthrough.andP;  IS officials would have preferred a more planned migration to 2.0.andO;Who can blame them?andP;  Seventy percent of the insurer's business is booked onits LANs.andM;Just as the company was digging out from the upgrade, 3Com pulled the plug on3andplus;Open and announced, &quot;Microsoft is your strategic partner now.&quot;andM;The company is still sorting it all out.andM;IS managers were grilled about when they first knew of 3Com's decision tovacate the network operating system business.andP;  The implications ranged fromconspiracy to incompetence.andM;The importance of a thorough examination of a vendor's strategy, financialhealth and overall stability cannot be underestimated.andP;  Regardless, no amountof scrutiny and diligence can ward off abrupt changes in vendor strategy.andO;After all, it's not who you can trust, it's how long you can trust them.andP;  --andO;John Dodge</TEXT></DOC>